<div id="comment_64516603" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64516603" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64516603" name="comment_link_64516603" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23342863&amp;cid=64516603" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64516603)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64516603" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64516603); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~RockDoctor">RockDoctor</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~RockDoctor">( 15477 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64516603"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64516603"><blockquote><div><p>now it's the high elevation or deeper resources left</p></div></blockquote><p>High elevation isn't that much of a problem. Every orebody that is worth mining at (say) 5km elevation has sections at 3 km elevation, so you tunnel into <b>those</b> (a one-off cost) at 3km elevation (about airliner pressurisation level) and haul your ore out that way, after bringing the roof down in a controlled manner. If the ore body is worth developing, you can swallow that billion dollars set-up cost.
</p><p>Once you've got the roof clear, you can move your benefi<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64516603">

</div>
