<div id="comment_status_64516347" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64516347" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64516347" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64516347" name="comment_link_64516347" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23342863&amp;cid=64516347" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64516347)" >doesn't pass the sniff test</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64516347" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64516347); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~dfghjk">dfghjk</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~dfghjk">( 711126 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64516347">		
		on Saturday June 01, 2024 @06:49PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23342863&amp;cid=64516347">#64516347</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64516347"><p>"On the other hand, hybrid electric vehicle manufacture would require negligible extra copper mining..." the report points out.</p><p>This could only be true if the extra copper demand was not in the vehicles themselves.  If that were the case, what they're really saying is that if we don't achieve significant electrification, then we won't need extra copper.  Duh.</p><p>A hybrid vehicle has all the ICE components plus a functional electric drivetrain.  There is no way a hybrid vehicle's copper demand is only "negligibly" more than ICE.  And it would need to be a plug-in electric, otherwise it accomplishes little toward electrification.</p><p>Just another oil-funded smear.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64516347">
